toString.name: toString
toString.comment:
Returns a string representation of (some of) the elements of this.

Elements are represented by their own toString results.

The representation always contains the first three elements. If there are less than a hundred elements in the iterable, it also contains the last two elements.

If the resulting string isn't above 80 characters, more elements are included from the start of the iterable.

The conversion may omit calling toString on some elements if they are known to now occur in the output, and it may stop iterating after a hundred elements.

hashCode.name: hashCode
hashCode.comment:
Get a hash code for this object.

All objects have hash codes. Hash codes are guaranteed to be the same for objects that are equal when compared using the equality operator ==. Other than that there are no guarantees about the hash codes. They will not be consistent between runs and there are no distribution guarantees.

If a subclass overrides bot/bot.Enumerable.hashCode it should override the equality operator as well to maintain consistency.

runtimeType.name: runtimeType
runtimeType.comment: A representation of the runtime type of the object.

iterator.name: iterator
iterator.comment: Returns an Iterator that iterates over this Iterable object.

length.name: length
length.comment:
Returns the number of elements in this.

Counting all elements may be involve running through all elements and can therefore be slow.

isEmpty.name: isEmpty
isEmpty.comment: Returns true if there is no element in this collection.

isNotEmpty.name: isNotEmpty
isNotEmpty.comment: Returns true if there is at least one element in this collection.

first.name: first
first.comment:
Returns the first element.

If this is empty throws a dart-core.StateError. Otherwise this method is equivalent to this.elementAt(0)

last.name: last
last.comment:
Returns the last element.

If this is empty throws a dart-core.StateError.

single.name: single
single.comment:
Returns the single element in this.

If this is empty or has more than one element throws a dart-core.StateError.

==.comment:
The equality operator.

The default behavior for all dart-core.Objects is to return true if and only if this and bot/bot.Enumerable.==.other are the same object.

Override this method to specify a different equality relation on a class. The overriding method must still be an equivalence relation. That is, it must be:

  • Total: It must return a boolean for all arguments. It should never throw or return null.

  • Reflexive: For all objects o, o == o must be true.

  • Symmetric: For all objects o1 and o2, o1 == o2 and o2 == o1 must either both be true, or both be false.

  • Transitive: For all objects o1, o2, and o3, if o1 == o2 and o2 == o3 are true, then o1 == o3 must be true.

The method should also be consistent over time, so equality of two objects should not change over time, or at least only change if one of the objects was modified.

If a subclass overrides the equality operator it should override the bot/bot.Enumerable.hashCode method as well to maintain consistency.

toString.name: toString
toString.comment:
Returns a string representation of (some of) the elements of this.

Elements are represented by their own toString results.

The representation always contains the first three elements. If there are less than a hundred elements in the iterable, it also contains the last two elements.

If the resulting string isn't above 80 characters, more elements are included from the start of the iterable.

The conversion may omit calling toString on some elements if they are known to now occur in the output, and it may stop iterating after a hundred elements.

noSuchMethod.name: noSuchMethod
noSuchMethod.comment:
bot/bot.Enumerable.noSuchMethod is invoked when users invoke a non-existent method on an object. The name of the method and the arguments of the invocation are passed to bot/bot.Enumerable.noSuchMethod in an dart-core.Invocation. If bot/bot.Enumerable.noSuchMethod returns a value, that value becomes the result of the original invocation.

The default behavior of bot/bot.Enumerable.noSuchMethod is to throw a dart-core.NoSuchMethodError.

map.name: map
map.comment:
Returns a lazy dart-core.Iterable where each element e of this is replaced by the result of f(e).

This method returns a view of the mapped elements. As long as the returned dart-core.Iterable is not iterated over, the supplied function bot/bot.Enumerable.map.f will not be invoked. The transformed elements will not be cached. Iterating multiple times over the the returned dart-core.Iterable will invoke the supplied function bot/bot.Enumerable.map.f multiple times on the same element.

where.name: where
where.comment:
Returns a lazy dart-core.Iterable with all elements that satisfy the predicate test.

This method returns a view of the mapped elements. As long as the returned dart-core.Iterable is not iterated over, the supplied function test will not be invoked. Iterating will not cache results, and thus iterating multiple times over the returned dart-core.Iterable will invoke the supplied function test multiple times on the same element.

expand.name: expand
expand.comment:
Expands each element of this dart-core.Iterable into zero or more elements.

The resulting Iterable runs through the elements returned by bot/bot.Enumerable.expand.f for each element of this, in order.

The returned dart-core.Iterable is lazy, and calls bot/bot.Enumerable.expand.f for each element of this every time it's iterated.

contains.name: contains
contains.comment: Returns true if the collection contains an element equal to bot/bot.Enumerable.contains.element.

forEach.name: forEach
forEach.comment: Applies the function bot/bot.Enumerable.forEach.f to each element of this collection.

reduce.name: reduce
reduce.comment:
Reduces a collection to a single value by iteratively combining elements of the collection using the provided function.

Example of calculating the sum of an iterable:

iterable.reduce((value, element) => value + element);

fold.name: fold
fold.comment:
Reduces a collection to a single value by iteratively combining each element of the collection with an existing value using the provided function.

Use bot/bot.Enumerable.fold.initialValue as the initial value, and the function bot/bot.Enumerable.fold.combine to create a new value from the previous one and an element.

Example of calculating the sum of an iterable:

iterable.fold(0, (prev, element) => prev + element);

every.name: every
every.comment: Returns true if every elements of this collection satisify the predicate test. Returns false otherwise.

join.name: join
join.comment:
Converts each element to a dart-core.String and concatenates the strings.

Converts each element to a dart-core.String by calling bot/bot.Enumerable.toString on it. Then concatenates the strings, optionally separated by the bot/bot.Enumerable.join.separator string.

any.name: any
any.comment: Returns true if one element of this collection satisfies the predicate test. Returns false otherwise.

toList.name: toList
toList.comment:
Creates a dart-core.List containing the elements of this dart-core.Iterable.

The elements are in iteration order. The list is fixed-length if bot/bot.Enumerable.toList.growable is false.

toSet.name: toSet
toSet.comment: Creates a dart-core.Set containing the elements of this dart-core.Iterable.

take.name: take
take.comment:
Returns an dart-core.Iterable with at most bot/bot.Enumerable.take.n elements.

The returned dart-core.Iterable may contain fewer than bot/bot.Enumerable.take.n elements, if this contains fewer than bot/bot.Enumerable.take.n elements.

It is an error if bot/bot.Enumerable.take.n is negative.

takeWhile.name: takeWhile
takeWhile.comment:
Returns an Iterable that stops once bot/bot.Enumerable.takeWhile.test is not satisfied anymore.

The filtering happens lazily. Every new Iterator of the returned Iterable starts iterating over the elements of this.

When the iterator encounters an element e that does not satisfy bot/bot.Enumerable.takeWhile.test, it discards e and moves into the finished state. That is, it does not get or provide any more elements.

skip.name: skip
skip.comment:
Returns an Iterable that skips the first bot/bot.Enumerable.skip.n elements.

If this has fewer than bot/bot.Enumerable.skip.n elements, then the resulting Iterable is empty.

It is an error if bot/bot.Enumerable.skip.n is negative.

skipWhile.name: skipWhile
skipWhile.comment:
Returns an Iterable that skips elements while bot/bot.Enumerable.skipWhile.test is satisfied.

The filtering happens lazily. Every new Iterator of the returned Iterable iterates over all elements of this.

As long as the iterator's elements satisfy bot/bot.Enumerable.skipWhile.test they are discarded. Once an element does not satisfy the bot/bot.Enumerable.skipWhile.test the iterator stops testing and uses every later element unconditionally. That is, the elements of the returned Iterable are the elements of this starting from the first element that does not satisfy bot/bot.Enumerable.skipWhile.test.

firstWhere.name: firstWhere
firstWhere.comment:
Returns the first element that satisfies the given predicate bot/bot.Enumerable.firstWhere.test.

If none matches, the result of invoking the bot/bot.Enumerable.firstWhere.orElse function is returned. By default, when bot/bot.Enumerable.firstWhere.orElse is null, a dart-core.StateError is thrown.

lastWhere.name: lastWhere
lastWhere.comment:
Returns the last element that satisfies the given predicate bot/bot.Enumerable.lastWhere.test.

If none matches, the result of invoking the bot/bot.Enumerable.lastWhere.orElse function is returned. By default, when bot/bot.Enumerable.lastWhere.orElse is null, a dart-core.StateError is thrown.

singleWhere.name: singleWhere
singleWhere.comment: Returns the single element that satisfies bot/bot.Enumerable.singleWhere.test. If no or more than one element match then a dart-core.StateError is thrown.

elementAt.name: elementAt
elementAt.comment:
Returns the bot/bot.Enumerable.elementAt.indexth element.

The bot/bot.Enumerable.elementAt.index must be non-negative and less than bot/bot.Enumerable.length.

Note: if this does not have a deterministic iteration order then the function may simply return any element without any iteration if there are at least bot/bot.Enumerable.elementAt.index elements in this.
